Balance is key.
-
Ensuring you're balancing your exercises out, or else there will be a cause for imbalance. For example, if you were to perform pushing exercises (eg. Bench press) more than pulling exercises (eg. Bent over rows), an imbalance in tension in the body will be created, and therefore shoulder and chest tightness will occur. This will ultimately lead to poor posture and possible injury down the line.
-
Same goes for your legs. If you're not working on the foundation of your structure, you're going to have a lack of support. Concentrating on the legs will allow for support in the bench press and bent over rows, as well as many other movements. The power you produce from your lower body will translate to upper body power too.
-
It's important to include variations and balance in movements for a positive overall development, not to mention optimal fat loss or muscle gain due to major motor unit recruitment (multiple muscles working).
-
Balance is important in the gym, and in life! Stay balanced peeps! 🙏

I was searching for a new moisturising concealer and settled on the Too Faced Born This Way Concealer ($40) in the shade Light. This claims to have an undetectable, natural finish due to a blend of colour correctors and is infused with coconut water, Alpine rose and hyaluronic acid. This is a lightweight formula that blends out easily and gives a brightening effect, but it has a radiant natural finish that struggles to completely hide dark circles. I had to go in with an extra layer on Monday morning 😴 just to cover minimal shadows from a lack of sleep. I do like the finish of this concealer though, and it lived up to its promise of illuminating and hydrating my *cough* aging under eye skin. Concealer will crease on me because I'm not 20, but it's very minor and doesn't settle into lines throughout the day. This reminds me of Nars Radiant Creamy, but less pigmented, and Maybelline Fit Me, but more hydrating. 15 countries, 31 cities, 1 island, 16986 kilometers away from home, 6 months later, a heavy heart and luggage (no joke), and I am still in denial about leaving Manchester. 
Over the past 6 months being abroad, I have had the greatest privilege in meeting such wonderful and amazing people from around the world that have made my exchange experience incredible. I know that I will miss seeing the buzzing bee logos around town, the casual outbursts of drunkards in broad daylight, the cheap alcohol, the crazy night life that Manchester is known for, the never ending arch of dirty mouldy dishes in Fallowfield flats, the England slang, the warmth from the sun rays during icy cold days, Sainsbury’s sandwich meal deals, the Magic bus, the wonderful architecture, the proximity to literally everything- from getting into town, to having late night drunk snacks/drinks across Fallowfield to travelling around Europe, my back aching spring-felt bed, also the idea that university was really only for two weeks (cough). But what I will mostly miss is the thrill that entails the many spontaneous weekday/weekend trips around Europe and the idea of being surrounded by friends only a door knock away. 
Today I walk away not just from a country, or the people I have met, but with the memorable experiences that I have made in my second home. It’s finally time to fly back to my land down under, but thank you Manchester- you’ve been the greatest and I hope to see you and everyone else soon. May the next 8 people make their own mark inside the four familiar walls of Holly court flat 20 as I once did 🗺✈ #exchange #manchester #chunderparty #nostalgiahittinghard #sydneyabroad #longestflightever #lookingforvisa

Hallelujah! This sums me up to the tee this past week LOL. Don't get me wrong, I'm all about my regular holistic healthy lifestyle, where I eat vibrant, nutritious food 99% of the time, but seeing as I've been insanely sick (cheers to being run down😥😒) since last Thursday night (hot & cold chills, coughing fits + pounding migraines) I literally couldn't bring myself to stomach any of my usual healthy foods!...aka quinoa, sweet potato, greens etc 😷

The thought of any fresh foods made me wanna spew😣 #sorryfortmi - except for tomatoes on plain rice crackers with BUCKETS of lemon juice & pink salt + a tiny bit of avo if I was feeling it.

So I just ate that for a good few days till I got sick of it...The only things that I thought I could stomach were the foods that I HARDLY EVER eat, aka. moderately healthy #vegan indulgence foods...like burritos, veggie patties etc...There was only so much of those I could eat before I got sick of them haha... But I've been in the city for the past few days, so dinners (+ a few sneaky brekkies) have been in there & my reg #healthfoods have NOT...I repeat NOT...been on the cards lol #sorrynotsorry. I've been treating myself to what I feel like, what my body craves, as this makes me feel better, despite it not being the healthiest choice on the planet. But you gotta do what you gotta do aye!😋 So I'm not lying when I tell you Pad Thai, Peanut Satay + Roti, Coconut Rice, Oreo + Choc Vegan Slices & Pesto + Cheese Toasties have been a regular occurrence these past few days hahaha! #poakakunikuni 🐽🐷🐽🐷 Can't forget @loving_earth choc too...woops!😏😕 Excuse the life story, but this is to tell ya'll that a few treaties here and there is NOT the end of the world. We're all human, and not in any way perfect, so we've gotta quit trying to have control of everything. Life happens, sickness happens & sometimes as a result...with it comes indulgences hahaha #truestory

Be happy, eat to feel good & radiate good vibes! ✌🌟🌿🍓

WOLVERINES!

Okay so I know this is a terrible movie, but I love it. The original Red Dawn is great but there's something about this remake that I really enjoy.

It really confuses me because there really isn't anything in this movie that's actually good, but every single beat I'm completely engaged.

The whole thing just kinda feels like a game (*cough cough* Homefront) or some elaborate dream a kid would think of "what would you do if zombies were real?? Oh, I'd do this and this and then I'll survive by doing this" — the movie is essentially that but with North Korea.

It was cool seeing Josh Peck on the big screen though.

To be completely honest, it's not really worth watching but it's a pretty fun popcorn flick so if you're bored one night and it's on VOD, check it out.

Update on the past month ⬇️
Firstly I have been keeping good weight between 53-54kg which is awesome! 🥜🍯🥕
I have actually not been sick all winter and praying I continue my good health. 
The last couple of weeks I've been having pretty bad chest pains, which resulted in an emergency X-ray and review. My chest sounded not right, my oxygen levels were much lower than usual and resting heart rate higher than it has been for a while.  X-rays showed no change since April. Which is good as no more damage has been done and nothing serious is causing my chest pain. 👍
I am still not on any antibiotics and still have no real reason to be. 
I am still doing all my natural things and am starting a new supplement I found through the CF community. There is also another natural supplement and it's one that has good reviews about lung function increase. I am so incredibly excited at these findings and am so keen to see how they benefit me. 👊
I am confident I am going down the right track I feel at peace with my decision to go natural and clear my body of all the medications I've taken over the years. 
I have already seen so much healing in my body since doing this and I know there is more to come. ☺️
.
.

Late to the Louvre 🙊💁🏼😅 // Legit went to the Louvre with 30 mins to closing time just to see Da Vinci's Mona Lisa. Guys, you have no idea just how hard this visit was for me, but by golly was I determined. At one point on the train I did think if I died I wouldn't mind so much if it was after I'd seen the Mona Lisa... 😅😅It was approximately 38 degrees Celsius. I was in immense pain from the previously mentioned luggage injury, I had a horrible cold and my cough was setting of the pain in the ribs every time I did so. It wasn't the best experience en route to the Louvre but I'm happy I ventured out of my bed nook to see a sight before I had to leave. I give a lot of credit to the people who pretend their lives are perfect. .
Furthermore I give even more credit to those who have mastered the complete understanding that all is already perfect. .
.
.
Let's be real.. it is. It always is and if it doesn't feel that way, the lesson has not yet been learned. .
.
.
I am constantly coming back to The Power Of Now, where we learn that it is impossible to be both suffering and present. .
.
. 
It has been a month already since I left my home in Buffalo to move to Bali for an undetermined amount of time. My fears that kept me (mostly) complacent geographically until now have been coming up. The big fear is: I am away from my dad and Meeko (🐶) and they are getting older and their lives are going on and I'm not there. The subconscious and unconscious mind of mine have been playing a game of absolute madness where I wake up from my sleep.. anywhere.. in bed, on the plane, in the cab, on the beach.. in utter panic, tears, heart palpitating shortness of breath confusion. Why am I here and not with them? It is THE WORST devastating heart wrenching feeling that makes me question everything I'm doing here and want to book a ticket home IMMEDIATELY. .
.
Then... I check in. I remember that I did not make the decision to come here.. Spirit did. And I feel theirs. Daddy and Meeko.. I feel you here. And I am there. And I love you so so so so much .
.
.
(And everyone else I'm missing) (semi-blah) the end.

year after year, week after week, day after day, second after second. look after the look. we lose something, find it, hide it, smash it and smash it again. We treat old wounds with new ones, forget each other, washing down with a bitter cough medicine. easy to hell after each conversation about the old. we have not learned how to be adults. no the best mother in the world can tell you how painful it is to lose forever, to go forward, gradually forgetting the past. we all cry and we can not understand what to do now? when we, like, should feel, but inside dangerously empty? we are not used to scorching ice, as well as being not used to the fact that the sun no longer heats. in a scanty adult world, there is no concept of "together", on every street, face and body a bright sign "himself" burns. and you begin to get used to managing without someone else's help. time goes by, runs and disappears behind a strong curtain of the great nothing. after so many heavy farewells, you, if that, recall "I will help you forget me" and this becomes your motto for life. pain from betrayal, washing your own skin from other people's tracks and gluing your own torn heart become compulsory companions. once again wake up in the cold, grab the mobile and check the mail, hands are burning from the memory of other people's touches. zero messages. did not my mother tell you? people leave and this is normal
This hike was brought to you by 7/11 coffee, sour straps, and my ventolin inhaler.

One must see the Great Barrier Reef while in Australia 🐠
Of all the things that I was excited to see when I moved to Australia, the Great Barrier Reef was definitely at the top of the list. Finding Nemo is my all time favourite movie, and having the chance to see all of the aquatic beauty that lay beneath was a crazy thought to me. Of course part of this whole experience is diving the Reef and witnessing the beauty by being truly submerged underwater.
➰
After boarding our ship to the Reef, we sat down to fill out some paperwork. Crossing all the t's and dotting all the i's. After a few moments a dive instructor came by and took a look at our forms. I've had asthma since I was a kid. It's not terrible, but is generally induced when I'm sick or exercising. The instructor looked at my form and then back at me sadly. Of course at that moment I knew what was coming, but didn't want it to be true.
➰
I wasn't allowed to dive the Reef, because of my asthma. This revelation was quite sad, as I had been looking forward to this moment for so long. I then realized that I was on a boat, and that the moment was too wonderful to fret and be down. So instead I smiled, walked outside to the deck and sat under the shining sun.
➰
Instead of diving, we were still able to snorkel. To be quite honest, it was just as incredible. We saw all of the same things the divers did, but just from above. I got to see starfish, a shark, rainbow fish, amazing coral, school after school of fish, and best of all I saw nemo 🙊, hence the ridiculous smile on my face. Even though it wasn't exactly how I pictured it would be, it still ended up being incredible.
➰
Have you ever gone somewhere with the intention of doing something you just had to, but it didn't end up working out? #overdoseintravel

Classic Gently-coughs

He coughed continuously in an uncivilized manner and let out loud groans after every second one.

And he kept digging the forest floor, under the moonless night sky.

The silence seemed haunting.

Then all of a sudden, he dropped his spade and collapsed to the muddy ground, clutching his chest, as if trying to stop it from ripping out.

He grabbed his untidily and rashly stitched chest, as it oozed maroon mass of flesh and blood and stained his dirty clothes. He blindly fished the satchel, panting like a fish out of water, and brought the large glass bottle of whiskey out.

He swigged down half the bottle like a hungry and starving cannibal, stood up like a resurrecting corpse out of the grave and resumed his digging.

He dropped the black plastic bag inside the little ditch he accomplished digging up and covered it up with the dirt and soil back again.

The thing kept beating in there, until it decayed away and got feasted by the maggots.

🐟 B12 plays a key role in nerve function and the formation of red blood cells. B12 deficiency can lead to anaemia, fatigue, weakness, shortness of breath, heart palpitations, pale skin, issues with the GI tract, numbness, depression, muscle weakness, vision loss and memory loss. Vitamin B12 also plays an important role in the breakdown or metabolism of fats and carbohydrates and has a role in protein synthesis, which makes it a vital element in weight management.

Day 3 of India road trip.
—
Awake, and have been made ill by the dust. Can hardly between coughs breathe.
—
Out to temple early, where an elephant is blessing children with its trunk.
On the road by 7:30, quickly to discover that google maps has taken me the back route and that that gas station I let pass may have been the last for quite a long time.
—
Monkeys litter the roadside, feeding, linguistically enough, on litter, and there are dirt-villages about every 15km until the road turns itself to dirt and the villages disappear.
Perhaps there is not enough dirt in India to go round.
—
At last, a crossroads village of only semi-dirt at the foot of a hill made of large rocks, where a frightening woman serves the most delicious deep-fried masala dough and a hefty woman rips me off for coffee.
—
The countryside is bland and unpicturesque and at times looks like an unwashed desert. Zero elephants.
—
Arrive in Kumbokunam at midday with a very sore bottom.
The hotel I booked only has WiFi in the "lobby" (a desk and chair) so I find another, very expensive, but nicer.
—
I walk up to the one laptop repair place in town.
—
On the way I see a wet headless chicken and a wet dead calf. The mud huts are adjacent to hillocks of garbage weeping into ditches that run with oily water.
No place has ever made me more appreciative to be a Westerner and no place has made me more sure that we must guard more fiercely than we are doing against the forces of barbarism and decline.
THIS could be the world's future, and it gives me an idea for the new book.
—
The one laptop repair place in town has never before laid eyes on a MacBook. So I still cannot work.
—
Temple at dusk, and very impressed by the size, colour, and cleanliness of the temple.
Reminded of Ruskin—"What use is pretty stained glass inside your churches when outside you have the plagues of Egypt?"
—
Less religion + more soap = happier India.
—
I cannot wait to leave.
—
(P.S. This, but a fraction of my long and horrendous day. You can read it all in its frightening entirety simply by signing up to my Laughing Cavalier mailing list @
👉🏻joshvahvmphreys.com!)

Keratin hair straightening

Remember! Keratin does not straighten hair!

Only formaldehyde has straightening properties, which, in high concentrations, is a carcinogen, and in small (or rather very small) amounts, is a preservative.

The very first straightening compounds had pure formaldehyde. After the ban on its use, manufacturers technically removed formaldehyde from the composition, but in fact it remained there. I believe this is very deceiving for the consumer. Formaldehyde was replaced with “methylene glycol” or “methanediol”, which when used with water, gives us the pure formaldehyde at the outlet. It can cause the reactions of lacrimation and difficulty breathing. If you experience these symptoms during any hair treatment services, be aware that you are breathing formaldehyde.

IMPORTANT! If you see methylene glycol at the end of the ingredient list as part of a product, then you should not worry. Its concentration in this case is very small, and therefore it is used as a preservative.

As many of you already know, the keratin straightening / restoration / treatment procedure includes a hot phase. The manufacturer recommends using the temperature of the iron in the range of 210C-230C on every small hair section of hair 7-8 times (Note: 180C is a totally safe temperature, recommended for any hair). What happens to the hair? In the first 2-4 straightenings with a hot iron, disulphide bonds are destroyed and the hair turns into an incandescent melting consistence. This is when formaldehyde acts as a powerful preservative fixing a new shape. In the next 5-8 straightenings, keratin is sealed inside the hair, forming a so-called corset on which the new shape will hold. This is certainly an eerie stress for the hair!

Not every hair will withstand this test. For bleached and fine hair, this procedure is strictly not recommended. Despite all these overloads, after this procedure, and over time, the hair can recover and returning to its original curly state. Keratin is washed away, the disulphide bonds are restored, and the hair regains its former shape.

😋 Want to know the number one ingredient that makes most food in Thailand taste AMAZING? 👌

We don't use it much in Australia anymore... Starts with M... Three letters... Yep! You guessed it! Thai food is loaded with MSG! They sell packets of it on supermarket shelves here and it is added to eeeeeeverything. 
Mee came home from the market today with a really yummy lunch for us; a serve of pumpkin and egg and a pork salad. 🍜 After eating it, my heart started racing and POUNDING out of my chest, I felt dizzy and wobbly on my feet, my chest was tight and painful and I was coughing because my heart was pumping so hard. 
I said to Mee that I thought the cook may have put too much MSG in and I was dealing with my first experience of heart palpitations. Mee turned around and said, "yes, he put 100% of the white powder packet in! 😱 I tell him, 'too much', but he said 'no problem, delicious!'" For 4 hours, my heart rate sat above 100 and at one point, I counted 119 bpm. 💓 My usual resting heart rate is a steady 64. This was the first time I'd experienced a reaction to MSG whilst living here and the first time I'd experienced heart palpitations. It was actually scary. A child or elderly person would be very wise to seek medical advice quickly. 
If you're traveling to Thailand and you have already experienced a reaction to MSG or have an allergy to it, BE DILIGENT. 👀 I honestly can't think of a meal that might not have MSG in it. My advice would be to stick to the vegan restaurants, 💚🌱my favorites are @pureveganheaven in Chalong (go the falafel bowl 👌) and @nanabowls at lots of cafes around Phuket. 🌴

Schisandra chinensis is an incredible herb that has been used in traditional Chinese medicine for centuries. The fruit was used as a stimulant, tonic, antiseptic, astringent and relaxant and used primarily for promoting longevity, increasing physical and mental stamina and in addition used for coughs, fatigue, impotence, memory loss and nervous complaints. 
In western herbal medicine, we use Schisandra berries as an antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, adaptogen, immune modulating, liver protective, antitussive, astringent, nervine and sedative to support mental and physical stress, inflammatory disease, support liver function and toxicity, to assist in lowering cholesterol, reduce insomnia, support immune function and also to reduce excessive perspiration and night sweats. 
Not only does Schisandra have so many incredible benefits, the berries also contain: Vitamin C & E, iron, copper, manganese, zinc, magnesium, potassium and phosphorus making it a powerhouse! 
Schisandra can be contraindicated in some individuals or medical conditions so please speak to a practitioner before trying.

THE TEMPLE OF AGAPE || A timely flashback to this great pop-up from London 2014.
.
Brightly coloured signs adorned with words related to “love in all its forms” decorates this architectural installation that designers #MoragMyerscough and #LukeMorgan  created for a summer festival in #London.
.
The installation popped up in front of the #RoyalFestivalHall and incorporated a pitched roof entryway framed by neon motifs and words, including part of a quote from civil rights activist Martin Luther King Jr that reads, “I have decided to stick with love.”
.
.
Agape means the love of humanity, and is one of seven Ancient Greek themes of love on which the festival’s agenda was based.
.

Help When You Need It the Most

One of the most distressing sounds a parent can hear is their son or daughter gasping for breath. 
A couple of times over the years one of our kids have woken us up in the middle of the night by the sound of that distinct, hollow, croup cough. If it’s bad enough, we need to stay calm and get to the hospital.

Whenever I’ve arrived at Emergency with one of our precious kids in my arms, there are two things that I’m hoping for.

The first thing is sympathy. Even though the triage nurse may have already seen endless patients, I’m always grateful when the nurse shows sympathy and validates both my child’s suffering and my concern.

But I didn’t come all the way to the hospital at 2:00am for a hug from a nurse. I’ve come to get my son or daughter breathing again. The second thing I’m hoping for is that there is not only sympathy, but a solution.

Thankfully, the Austin Hospital Emergency department has consistently given us both sympathy and solutions we’ve need it the most.

We also have access to a helper with a greater capacity to help than any Emergency department. Jesus is always ready to answer our cry as soon as we run to Him, and He not only shows us great sympathy but also has the power to bring a solution to any problem: ‘Let us come boldly to the throne of our gracious God. There we will receive his mercy, and we will find grace to help us when we need it most’ - Hebrews 4:15-16 (NLT)

Jesus gets it. We all struggle at times. None of us are exempt from the temptations and hardships of life, not even the Son of God Himself, which is why He has unlimited compassion on us: ‘He understands our weaknesses, for he faced all of the same testings we do’ - Hebrews 4:15a (NLT)

Yet although Jesus was tempted in every way, He remained undefeated and ‘did not sin’ (4:15b). Now this victory over sin, temptation, the devil and even death is available to any one who puts their trust in Him: ‘Overwhelming victory is ours through Christ, who loved us’ - Romans 8:37 (NLT)

No matter what your need is, you can run to Jesus who will not only show you sympathy but being a solution to help you when you need it the most!

I am not looking forward to that at all. • "Everyone, please be welcoming to our newest member of the group." Lia said with a smile at the youths sitting around the room. "Perseus, why don't you take a seat next to—"
"Call me Percy." The redhead grinned, a dimple appearing in his left cheek. His eyes twinkled and he went to say more but stopped himself as he caught her eye, as if realising that maybe it wasn't appropriate.
It was common to get a range of personalities in a support group, Lia had found over the years, each in need of help with one thing or another. She had yet to speak to Percy on his own, but from his initial confidence, she couldn't help but want to assume that he'd be a simple case.
This is not how the next hour went.
Percy was a very imaginative boy, with stories that exceeded reality. He spoke highly of his family, who starred in his adventures, particularly his brothers and sisters—though he made it clear that they were only cousins and he only had one sister—but gave no specific names for them. His stories distracted the group from speaking of their own problems, or maybe they were aware that he would be taking up the time and taking advantage of the chance not to speak.
But then he stumbled after speaking a few words that struck Lia so suddenly that her breath caught in her throat and sent her in a coughing fit that turned the attention to her. Percy's story forgotten, Lia wondered if she'd imagined it when he'd said it, the name of the place his family lived.
Spatia Gehenna. •

🔹🔹 Moulds (Airborne) 🔹🔹 Related to yeasts and fungi. Can be a problem both indoors and outdoors, it will flourish in warm, moist conditions. Commonly a problem in kitchens, basements, bathrooms, air-conditioning systems,  saunas, swimming pools, greenhouses and other similar environments. 🌵House plants tend to increase the problem of moulds. 
One less commonly recognised source of mould spores is in lawns. As the grass is cut, mould spores will be released into the air from the surface layer of the soil. Outdoors, wet weather favours mould growth, and sunny windy weather favours the release of mould spores. 
Particularly implicated in asthma, allergic rhinitis and other general respiratory problems. Because mould spores are so small, it is possible for them to reach the finer tubes within the lungs. 
Other airborne moulds include Alternaria, Aspergillus, Cladosporium, Mucor and Penicillium. Other moulds found where water has been standing a long time include Fusarium, Trichoderma and Stachybotrys (picture). Main symptoms of mould toxicity are fatigue, muscle pain, joint and nerve issues, eye and visual disturbances, respiratory symptoms, cognitive issues, headaches, mood swings, vertigo, metallic taste in your mouth, night sweats, excessive thirst, increased frequency of urination. 🔹 Mould symptoms and Tick-bourne bacteria symptoms are all very much alike 🔹

Monthly immunoglobulin appreciation post ❤️ Finally receiving my IVIG today after 2 false starts last week. It's been half a year now since I started blood plasma infusions and I can't believe the difference it has made. In the past 6 months I have only had ONE(!!!!!!!!) cold. And it was uneventful, and completely gone after 2 weeks!
.
Over the past few years ever since my immunodeficiency really came into its own, developing a sniffle in my nose would fill me with ice-cold dread. A cold would inevitably turn into bronchitis with asthma (and sometimes pneumonia! or whooping cough!), it would take at least a month and a course or 2 of antibiotics to clear, and would then leave me in peace for only around 6 weeks before it or some variation of it returned. I thought it was normal to be on antibiotics every 2 months. I often accused people who claimed to not have had antibiotics in more than a year as liars 😂.
.
Not only is the IVIG fortifying my immune system, it’s also helping to regulate it! Whilst its mechanism is not entirely understood, immunoglobulin is thought to possibly slow progression of MS, and is also a first line treatment in cytopenias. So if it's helping to mitigate/prevent the 2 biggest shits in my life, I’m pretty okay with having junkie arms 💉💁🏼‍♀️

column11:
The day started off casual.

I woke up. Poured my coffee. Read. Laughed. Prayed. Meditated. Tackled some emails. Then proceeded to do my in-home workout.

I got into position to do some glute raises, and immediately, something felt... OFF.

Wildly off.

But I ignored it, because of course it's just me trying to talk myself out of this workout (as I do every morning 😭). But by my third set, I felt my eyes roll to the back of my head.

I lost my vision for a split second but when I got it back, the room was sideways and fuzzy.

I felt like someone was pushing me over and I was fighting this heavy weight *cough* gravity *cough* which was making my body feel like it wanted to collapse to the side.

Slightly panicked, but knowing that God wouldn't have me leave this Earth without putting on my brows, I remained calm as my friend poured me water.

And then it hit me.

How much caffeine have I been putting in my body lately? That morning, I just realized I put 3 cups of coffee roast in my small mug, oblivious to the amount, but just feeling like I needed the extra kick.

And the glute exercise had me in a downward position for 3 minutes, so blood rushing to my head mixed with the high caffeine level, was just a disaster waiting to happen.

I know I've had a problem with caffeine since college. But I rarely did anything to actively fight it.

Why do we convince ourselves we're invincible when our bodies slowly but surely deteriorate under the weight of our imaginary immunity?

I spent the next few hours nauseous and horizontal. [Is this what labor is like?! 😩] But why is it that when life politely taps our shoulder to remind us of our bad habits, we rather wait until disaster strikes?

So here's a reminder to you that whatever bad habit you've been trying to break -- don't wait any longer.

Your body, your health, and your mind deserve the purest version of you.

We're all a couple bad habits away from tapping into another realm of our greatest potential.

By sunset, my head was clear and my stomach was emptied 🤢. Lesson learned.

I'm excited to give this coffee-free life a go for a bit.

Any tips or healthier alternatives welcomed.

What's YOUR bad habit?

I have generalised anxiety disorder (GAD) which means my #anxiety is independent of external stimuli and is pretty much constant. I have physical #symptoms such as chest tightness, difficulties breathing sometimes, muscle tension, restlessness and #panic attacks. I used to worry a lot and avoiding things that cause me anxiety. Worrying excessively and #avoidance are unhelpful. I found having a #purpose in life and working through my psychological pain helped me to get to a much better mental state, in addition to a healthy lifestyle most of the time. You can find out your anxiety level by taking a 5 question checklist on #BeyondBlue website. Read about my experience on www.myautumnbloom.com on page anxiety and depression. It really is proof though that if you really need to get a Quick workout in no matter where you are or what equipment you have on you, it can be done! 💪🏼 This morning before we left our camper van park to get back in the road, I did a quick 25 minute AMRAP of the following circuit with our water supply 😋👇🏼
A1. Single arm rows (15 reps each arm) 
A2. Single leg RDL’s (15 reps)
A3. Single arm bicep curls (10 reps)
A4. Goblet squats 
A2. Upright rows (15 reps) 
A5. Overhead squats

Today’s blog is “Feeling Pooly”. Read a bit here here and the rest at weavethefuturemagical.com xxx
In a glass-cage of emotion: Louise Hay connects all physical symptoms to their emotional cause. I looked into the cause of my snot, sinus and cough in her book, “You can Heal Your Life” and found that they meant that there was ‘lack of clarity, frustration at someone close, overwhelm’. It is a very emotional time of year with a lot going on, plus it started with the full moon and the mercury retrograde (Dec 3-22) so it all made sense if you’re into that kinda thang. I said the affirmations and I visualised my body being healthy and strong. 
A day now saves a week later: Now unfortunately I didn’t do this one as I wanted to maintain my unblemished sick leave record. No Ferris Bueller’s day off for me (you’re not dying, you just can’t think of anything good to do). As soon as you feel the dreaded large coming on, if you can, it is best to stop, drop and roll. Dose up on all the lemon-ginger-honey drinks known to man and get into bed and sleep it off. Call in sick for a day now or you may be facing a week off later. I plan to get better at this one soon. No one has ever given me a bloody prize for not having a sick day but many who have worked with me when I have been poorly may well have wished I was more coherent. If you can, knock the illness on the head, dose up on home made remedies and recite affirmations until the cows come home. 
The worst has passed so I will take the air and the vapours and hope it won’t come to blood letting. Looking after myself better will continue to be an aim as 2017 turns to 2018. How do you cope with feeling poorly friend? 
Love and light and life moves pretty fast. If you don’t stop and look around once in a while, you could miss it. Xxx Yvette

column11:
|| A S T H M A || I’ve had mild asthma since I was 3, always suffering with respiratory issues and multiple chest infections as a child. My memory of every Christmas was me coughing and spluttering and often missing the school play as I was wrapped up at home on various antibiotics while the cat slept in my lap. As I got older my asthma pretty much vanished and these issues became a thing of the past. I’d occasionally have to use my puffer (ventolin inhaler) when the seasons changed or if I was near anything stuffed with feathers (awful on every level but that’s another topic) but for the most part I forgot about ever having asthma! That was until I moved to Sydney in November 😱 I don’t know if it’s new pollen in my system or dust mites but I now definitely have asthma again 😬 It’s by no means awful, but I’m using my inhaler at least once a day (they say to see a GP if you take it more than 3 times per week).
.
.
My recent (mild) asthma has encouraged me to look into specific yoga and pranayama that can help alleviate tightness in the chest and help open up the area. Back bending and heart opening postures can be really useful in opening the chest improving lung functionality. It may be good to practice upper back bends and chest opening postures if you find it is harder to exhale, and forward bends and lower back bending poses if you find it more difficult to inhale. Inverted postures can help drain excess mucus from the lungs and also help balance the immune system. .
.
It can also be helpful to incorporate more calming poses into your practice as these can help you cope in times of breathing difficulty and stress. I’ve found it really helpful to be able to slow down my breathing and calm my nervous system down - naturally we can panic whenever we are faced with breathing problems which can tighten the chest even more and lead to heightened anxiety. Being able to take calming breathes helps me restore normal breathing ✨Does anyone else have any tips for dealing with asthma and/or hay fever type allergies? I’m curious to know if anyone else got reacquainted with their asthma after moving to Australia (or anywhere else!) 🌬

Razia*, 7, lives with her parents, four brothers and sisters in the camps for the #Rohingya people in #Bangladesh. The family fled #Myanmar when extreme violence erupted there in August.

Razia's village was set on fire. The family hid for two days in the jungle. They managed to reach safety after eight days.

I sat with Razia in her makeshift shelter constructed from bamboo and flimsy plastic sheeting. "I was very scared when our village was on fire. I kept hoping that we would get to safety. At first we tried to cross the river (a natural border between northern #RhakineState in Myanmar and Bangladesh) but we didn't have any money so we could not cross. After, one boat was coming from Bangladesh so they asked to just board and go without any money, so we crossed the river. Now every time I see people in army uniform I get very scared and start to cry," said Razia.

Razia has escaped the horror of extreme violence. Now she faces a new peril, cold overnight winter temperatures. January and February are the coldest months in Bangladesh, yet in the camps it is common to see barefooted children wearing only thin cotton clothing, shorts and t-shirts. "It is very cold from the ground, the floor, and also water from the roof. That is why I have the cough. We only have four blankets for the whole family," added Razia.

#SavetheChildren is distributing winter kits to 7,000 families (31,000 people) in preparation for the coldest winter months. Winter kits contain blankets, shawls for adults, children's pullovers, slippers for adults and children as well as a floor mat. * The name has been changed to protect identity.
Left me breathless from the moment I stepped in. #Stunning

ADOPT A DISCIPLINED MINDSET
.
Discipline can be the greatest roadblock to achieving the success you desire! 
Below are our 5 top tips that can assist you in removing the discipline roadblock from your life ! .
1. Get committed: Once you've decided on a goal, make the commitment to achieve it. Give yourself a timeframe and set aside a specific day and time to measure your progress. If you can't be accountable for yourself then find someone else whom you can be accountable to - (Cough cough* The Alpha Babes) 😏
.
2.Stay focused: Visualise the success you wish to achieve and pick a quiet time or place to imagine the feeling of achieving your goal. Setting this time aside each day will assist in reminding you that you desire success more than an extra hours sleep in the morning or giving in to the temptation of a cheat day.
.
3. Prioritise: Determine what needs to be done first and get the hardest tasks out of the way in the morning. This will give you a sense of accomplishment and leave you with less time to make excuses for not doing them later in the day.
.
4. Look after your well-being: Achieving a disciplined mindset means you need to be disciplined in all areas of your life, not just one. Remember, you are working towards a new lifestyle which includes getting enough rest, exercise and eating well. .
5. Reward yourself: It is imperative to recognize your progress and celebrate your successes. This will increase your level of motivation and remind you to feel good about what you are achieving.
.

I'm home & alive DON'T WORRY! (Feel free to skip to Chapter 4 😂😂) Intro -

Safe to say 2017 was a bit of a rollercoaster from a personal point of view.
I haven't posted anything about my time in hospital since i was there in April & May so i don't come off as a little attention seeker... But all in all... it was a great life learning experience!

Chapter One -

2 seperate stints in the intensive care unit and those close to me know how close everything was to being the end too. Completely out of nowhere and out of the blue. Waking up with slight chest pains... to having the worst pains imaginable in the space of 12hrs.
Having shit experiences in there from overdosing me with laxatives (no pun intended) lol, to making me choke when putting me under anaesthetic before surgery... to inserting I.V drips into the wrong part of my arm, (to the point my forearm was about double the size and looking like quagmire when he finds out about the internet), where i was in pain galore but didn't ask for help until i reallyyy knew something was wrong and the nurses freaked out lol
Note: That's only a few if my incidents!!
But everyone's msgs and support kept spirits high and made me laugh. 
Yep, i remember everyone's msgs' or visits and won't forget! From here and overseas. People I've known my entire life, to my aunty that came straight away from greece... to wishes and prayers from people I've never met in my life! And they were all just as touching ❤
Spirits were that high, i was giving shit to a student male nurse that came to take my blood. He was nervous as could be, didn't even know how to sterilize properly, then once the needle went in, i yelped like it hurt and started laughing... not too long after, he saw the blood coming out, let his jittery hands off my arm and got the female nurse to take over while he went and collapsed in the hallway 😂😂😂 Must admit.. that was hilarious! Lol
Then there was when the doctors told me i had cancer infront of my family, i was keen and eager to take it on! I swear i felt like superman with everyone around me!

I'm not about to bore you with the cliche "#2017 has been rough" line. We all know that. We all experienced it. Instead, I'll say that this year was necessary. It helped shape a lot of who we are and who we wish to become.

Going into the #2018 I can only hope we continue to grow, continue to be better and do better. Continue to trust the ones around us and hold accountable the people we care about. Most of all, continue to be true to ourselves.

As for #WhiskyArch, we want to thank everyone who has been on this journey with us. Before and after the relaunch. We hope to maintain your support as we try new things, and if we don't, hey, no love lost.

Speaking of love, figured it was only right to end the year with a few of my favourite drams. Everything from @usmacallan to @laphroaig. From @jimbeamofficial #Bookers to @thesmws. Missing a couple stand outs from my year though (*cough*#snowphoenix*cough*). What really made this night though, beyond the amazing #whisky, were the #friends I shared these drams with. Because afterall, that's what's most important in #mywhiskylife.

Cheers and #happynewyear,
Peat

🏅🏊‍♂️✔ 2018 Personal Achievement: SCUBA dived the Great Barrier Reef! 🦈
.
Having a pre-existing medical condition (mild asthma) often completely bars prospective divers from SCUBA activities in strict-safety regions of the world like Australia. I took a diving medical examination, passed, and successfully dived in three of the outer reefs that comprise the world's greatest coral reef system: the Great Barrier Reef.
.
Although the reef is certainly in visible, physical decline due to a number of human-driven factors, there were still thousands of colorful coral types, fish, anemone, sea turtles, squid, giant human-sized clams that close really quickly (and creepily), sea cucumbers, and even a stray mantra ray and very small shark! Looking forward to the underwater pictures. There are some good ones to share!
.
Thank you Quicksilver and the Silverswift crew (and especially Yuta!) for a fantastic, full day out on the reef. You guys were the best. Now for certification! 🤙🏼😎

An evening slowly set to laying blue across the city. I was walking all alone, and in the growing shade the sounds of traffic mingled with the bated hum that fell like vapor down from building's tops where heaters swallowed air and belched exhaust. Memories of nights at home, of how the moonlight dampens noise as if the darker air is thicker, too, began to slip like threads within my mind--tenuous at first, but gaining favor as the light resigned to make the sharper lines of things a bit more soft. A man approached me on the sidewalk, asked if I'd a pound to spare.

Scattered planes of light began to blink into existence, conspicuous against the glassy shadows of the architecture framing them. The people inside twisted shut their blinds or slid their curtains closed, worried, maybe, that down here on the streets an eye might stray. Though I'm inclined to think it much the opposite: that dimming streets afforded not the taintless views that they'd inclined. A pound to spare.

Several thousand miles away my mother fed a large and aging dog who I love dearly. I phoned her in the evenings just to see how they'd been getting on, and usually she'd hold the phone for him so that his rapid breaths could crackle in the speaker. He didn't understand me, but I'd plainly ask him how his day had been, what he'd done while I was gone and if, by chance, he'd cleaned the house. His breath would tell me no.

On the sidewalk there in London, early spring and verging stormy weather every instant, I held the coins inside my pockets so their heedless noise might break a bit less sharply in the muslin evening falling grey and free and futile. A song for every memory in dusky hours. Some of them are soft, some of them the blue is deep and some so pale they barely have a grain. And it was memory, the voice I'd heard implore me for some change. A simple memory to pass like so much doubt and walk away. And I suppose but for scenery they render all the same.

Have you got a Himalayan salt lamp? 
These lamps emit negative ions to neutralize electromagnetic radiation - it's super beneficial to have these placed around electrical items around the house such as near a computer/laptop.

They've also been used in treating Seasonal Affective disorder as their light mimics the sun's rays.

One of the best benefits though is their help in battling allergies and asthma! As someone who constantly has hayfever and other various allergies - this is one of the biggest benefits that I've noticed since placing one on my bedside table 2 years ago!

I tackled the Kokoda Track Memorial Walk with a buddy today 👯‍♀️ What better time to post my review on Man Alive by @jordanptravers. Jordan is a holistic fitness coach who has written this book to help people transform their health & reap the benefits of better nutrition, more movement & time spent in nature 🍃🌳
•
I’ve gotta say, Man Alive provided me with a bit of a wake up call. While I’m relatively health conscious, I’ve experienced years of hayfever, eczema, anxiety, muscle aches, digestive problems & recently diagnosed asthma. Bundled together, these symptoms lead to a few frustrations & general fatigue. I really enjoyed Jordan’s concise, no-nonsense approach to achieving optimum health & have already implemented some of his top tips. It’s a jungle out there when we try to understand the latest diet fads & exercise programs.
•
Man Alive provides factual info & relevant resources for you to do more research & make your own choice about the products you use & the food you eat. Jordan’s passion & excitement for good health really shines through; expect zero mumbo jumbo & a good sense of humour from this one! While it’s aimed at men & their physiology, there is a lot of excellent advice that you can take on board whether male or female. Stay tuned for an exciting comp I’ll be running soon! 🤗

Secondly, I just couldn’t work out the logistics of getting out between feeds/sleeps/changing. 🤔

Our fam of 4 went out to lunch (and nobody cried), we went for a walk along the beach (and nobody cried) and we even went to the supermarket (ok, Baby Wolverine did cry but it was his feed time - I’ll forgive him for that one). THROWBACK THURSDAY - THE LION KING Melbourne 2005
-
Even though I saw this show nearly 13 years ago, I still rave about how magical it was to this day.
-
The "Circle of Life" opening number is by far my favourite opening of any show. I teared up when I saw the elephant coming down the aisle and the monkeys hanging from the ceiling.
-
This show-stopping, lump-in-your-throat opening really set the scene and, I thought, celebrated its African setting. It also overwhelmed the audience as it brought all the savannah animals onto the stage.
-
Prior to the show, I remember thinking how they were going to bring the animals to life. After all, there are no humans in the movie. But when I saw the use of and detail in the puppetry used, I was blown away. The actors' movements to bring the puppetry to life was nothing short of breathtaking. It revealed the complexities and emotions experienced by each of the characters.
-
Whilst the whole cast was amazing, the show-stopper for me was Buyisille Zama, as Rafiki. I was floored by her performance (albiet a small but important part in the entire show) especially when she called up all the animals to the stage for the presentation of Simba.  AMAZING.
-
Overall, I was blown away by the dazzling colours, soulful music, inticate but detailed costumes and the extraordinarily realistic bodily manifestations of all the animals. The Lion King, in all its glory, had come alive!
-
It was big, heart-warming and stunningly beautiful with music that made your heart race and puppetry that made you gasp. It was simply brilliant.

MANHATTAN BEACH, CA: Miss Maisel may be 8 years old but she is still very much The Energizer Bunny! She is playful yet cuddly, and puppy-like yet mature. Sound perfect? That's because she is! Maisel would do well with friendly canine playmates at home and will slip into your family routine as if she has always been there. She is a gem! She has been up for adoption since last September. 
PLEASE SHARE to help Maisel find her forever family! 🐰🐰 The Dexter Foundation wrote, "Sweet Maisel sat in the shelter for nearly three months! She was a volunteer favorite and they often took her out just to cuddle, which is one of her specialties. Eventually, Maisel was put on the 48 hour euthanasia list. When we heard about her, we knew we had to save her! 
After three months in the shelter, Maisel arrived pretty beat up. She had rotten teeth, had gained a lot of weight from inactivity, had serious eye and skin infections and finally kennel cough. We had Maisel treated by our vet including a full dental and senior blood work. She is completely healthy and has no chronic medical issues. 
Maisel is now in foster care and has two active young terriers foster siblings who took to Maisel immediately. The three of them play constantly, and little Maisel has already lost 4 pounds! She runs around like a puppy and is very happy. Maisel also loves to nap in the sun, loves to cuddle by your side and has the best house manners. She is fully house trained, quiet, not at all destructive or barky, and doesn't dig or chew. She walks like a lady on a leash and doesn't pull. She is very well behaved in the car as well. The marvelous Miss Maisel is practically perfect! 
Maisel is only about 8 years old, and for a dog her size, that's barely middle-aged. She is a total love bug and will bring a lot of joy into any home. She is very easy to adopt, and even easier to love. 
We're looking for a forever home for Maisel in the #SouthernCalifornia area." To adopt Maisel, please email The Dexter Foundation at contactus@dexterfoundation.com with any questions or to submit your application. ❤️ #seniordog #chihuahua #adoptme #california #adoptdontshop

As you must have guessed now, I'm obsessed with the sea. But if you see my camera roll, you'll know what the true definition of 'obsession' means. But let me tell you why I love the sea so much...
.
Have you ever felt claustrophobic in a room full of people you know? Or even in an open space, not bound by walls? Have you ever felt like escaping for a little while, to a beautiful island where there aren't too many people, no noise, blue waters. Have you ever felt out of place in your own hometown? Or have you felt so fed up living the same routine every single day for years and wanted to break free, just for a little while? Has someone who means the world to you ever broken your heart, and have you ever just needed some space to breathe? Not that you can't breathe, but you can't...if you know what I mean. So, having grown up in a town where the sea was only a couple of minutes away, I found myself going there everytime I needed comforting, or just some space to breathe and time to think. 
I find it very interesting how the sea can make you remember things you want to forget, and forget things you never want to forget. There's something hypnotizing about how the waves crash on the shore and retreat. If you're really upset and crying and sitting by the beach, you'll see that the tears stop falling when you start listening to the waves. And for a second, nothing really matters. You start taking deep breaths, feel the air fill your lungs, you look at the horizon and some memories come rushing back...all the good times you've spent with people on the beach, and also the bad times that you don't want to face. But somehow you get through it. You see the vastness of the ocean, look around and see the empty beach... it's one of the best feelings in the world! .
.
.
.
.

NEW BOOK TEASER: Introducing Maika, the novels badass tritagonist - enjoy: “The murmurs die down as the class settles in and draws their attention back to Mr. Fitch. “Thank you,” he smiles, “ok good morning future Prime Ministers, Architects, Stay at home Dads, DJs, Marine Biologists and Club Bouncers” everyone laughs, “on the off chance you’ve forgotten, you have a quiz on Immanuel Kant this Friday.” Everyone groans. “I know, I’m the worst. It’s almost as if I’m your teacher and I care about your education.” They laugh again. Mr. Fitch always knows how to work the class. “Also, we have a new student joining us.” He gestures to the centre of the room where a girl with long blonde hair is sitting, drawing flowers on her arm in blue pen. She’s wearing faded denim overalls and a backwards cap. She looks at Mr. Fitch and smiles. “Maika has just moved here from The Netherlands and will be joining us for the rest of year.” She’s sitting down but I can tell she’s tall. Even with one arm leaning against the back of her chair and slouching, her eyes are still an inch above everyone else’s heads. “Maika, could you tell the class a little bit about yourself?”
“Sure.” She shrugs and Fitch smiles again. “Cool, the stage is yours.” He says, taking a seat. She stands up, clears her throat and waves. “I’m Maika; 17, Dutch, non-alcoholic. This is my second time living in Montreal, my family move around a lot. I play various sports and read a lot of sci-fi. I can hold my breath for a really long time. Oh and I love skittles. Preferably lemon.” She smiles, sitting back down. The class begin to murmur again. From the back of the room, Patrick Macmillan pretends to cough the word ‘freak’ under his breath making his friends laugh. Maika looks at Patrick unfazed. It’s almost as if she didn’t hear what he said even though she definitely did because, well, we all did. She looks back at Mr. Fitch and stands up for a second time. “I’m also a feminist, a vegetarian and, you know, a total freak.” And just like that, the class explodes into laughter. Mr. Fitch clears his throat to stop himself from smirking as Patrick turns bright red, sinking deep into his chair, embarrassed.

M E S M E R I S E D | 'Let's wander where the wifi is weak'... Just Wow! I totally now understand why people choose to live away from the city, and in the country area. I will probably one day be one of those people ☺️ I never thought I'd say this, but going to my 1st ever hike was overwhelming beautiful! I used to think; 'Why would people choose to walk for hours just to go see the view? So crazy! And pointless!' Yep, I was one of those people. #shame 😅 Yet, the serene feeling experienced is just magical. Nature is truly breath-taking. Working in the city, driving in the traffic and constantly being among people, and then walking through this silence nothing but the sounds of trees, birds and that 'breeze' you feel... is truly something that made my heart feel special. I've realised how caught up I have become in my busy work life, being indoors, constantly connected to some kind of technology, the stresses of life.... to stepping away from it all, is nothing but freedom I felt today. Refreshing and reenergising. Why haven't I ever done this before I wondered? and yes, must admit I couldn't talk properly going uphill because I was out of breath haha, and yes, walking twice with a stick to support me and then throwing it into the bush when people were walking towards us... and saying to @anee90 'Let's act cool, like we are not dying as we can't breath just for 6 seconds enough to walk past them haha' this all happened! And must admit, everyone walking past us all we're so friendly, smiling and said to us 'Hi, how's it going? literally I thought all the happy people are here, my people are here I've found them!! Loved it! Gr8 time spent with @anee90 💜 love you! Looking forward to returning to where my heart felt peace once again! Who's in to join? ☺️ #16km #hike #mtmacedon #melbourne #thehijabnurse #nurseoffduty #justdoit

This is me. I’m a size 12/14. I’m not an alien, I’m not abnormal and I’m not shock value. I’ve rarely gone into a store and worried they won’t have my size (ok, Kookai cough) but lately I’ve felt a distinct lack of on trend options in my size. A lot of these boutique brands seem to carry up to an xl which only seems to correspond to a 12 or 14 at most. Where are the options? When are these brands going to understand that a want to be stylish does not just stop at a size 10.  If I’m struggling, I hate to think what it’s like as a bigger size (I raise a glass to you ladies). Trust me, I’ve heard ALL the excuses of it costing more to extend your size range but in this day and age I think it’s irrelevant. It’s 2018.  Maybe I’m destined to do all my shoots in my knickers. What are your thought? @lililand @bellamanagement

Here in Melbourne, the summer season is a time of intense heat and dryness with bouts of cold and rain that increase as we approach autumn. Murray River - Doolans Bend Camping Area

#FREECAMP
Our first camp on the mighty #MurrayRiver!  The Murray is one of the places I have been looking forward to visiting since we left on our adventure . Located about 20 minutes out of Albury–Wodonga and even closer to the small town of Chilton . This camp site did not disappoint. We setup right on the river bank watching the kids splash and play in the shallow waters by the rivers edge, feeling as though we could be the only people left in the world...
Then down the river "Old mate" cranked up the noisiest old generator ever built. It seriously sounded like King Kong trying to bash his way out of a cage 😂. Yep.. it ran till after 10pm when it coughed and spluttered for a few minutes finally slowing down and stopping leaving a deafening silence as the sedative must have kicked in. 😉

We stayed for several days fishing, playing and just 'chilling out' at this fantastic camp site until we had to move on due to commitments elsewhere!  #onedayweshould return to the area to explore further along the banks of this awesome river!
-Gibbo

Everyone knows that dietary fibre is good for you, but wow - didn't realise what it was capable of until my nutrition class today!! It is the indigestible part of plants found in veggies, fruit, whole grains and legumes. Did you know that fibre can literally absorb carcinogens and other toxins? Seriously insane!! Short chain fatty acids created are great for healthy gut bacteria as well. This means fibre is really great at aiding anti-inflammatory diseases and others too - including diabetes, arthritis, coronary heart disease and asthma.

The only think to be mindful of, when increasing fibre intake - water intake needs to be increased too to look after the extra load.

Why aren't we reaching for more fibre in our diets when it's so beneficial to us?

6 months ago I closed the door on my corporate career and opened up my business @thelowtoxfox .
I was very sick and in hospital 2 years ago, to be honest and without being totally dramatic I was lucky to survive, after that I would go to work and think ‘what am I doing with my life?’ .
I was so unfulfilled moving numbers around on spreadsheets, I wanted my life to mean something, to help my community and actually have an impact
.
Leaving my high paying corporate job was scary, and some days I still wonder if I’m crazy, but when I have customers come in and tell me their sons asthma has completely disappeared after switching to the cleaning products I recommended it makes me realise I’m doing exactly what I’m meant to be doing and that I absolutely love it 💚
